node.text:
Watch this short video by @kabuki_virtualcoaching coaches @bmorg33 and @colbs_cass_lifts to learn more on why lumbar extension can lead to many issues and is not optimal for movement under load. We first need to understand WHY it is happening. The two most common reasons it tends to happen are:

▪️Chest up leading to poor hinge mechanics. We need to let ones chest hinge forward.

▪️Poor breathing patterns leading to a lack of IAP being built and spine stability jeopardized.

Once we understand why it is happening we can make strides to fix it thus decreasing injury risk and improving our ability to handle load.
 
Make sure to follow @kabuki_virtualcoaching for more educational videos like this one.

Learn the Bird Dog as presented by @kabuki_virtualcoaching coaches @brandon_senn and @colbs_cass_lifts
-
The bird dog exercise is one of the most common exercises prescribed by rehab pros for low back pain and dysfunction. Even if you aren't in pain its a fantastic drill to learn how to move your hips and shoulders off of a stable core. It can improve your shoulder stability for overhead pressing and even your hinge mechanics in a squat and deadlift. However, due to its popularity, it tends to be an exercise that is performed incorrectly more often than not. If you can master the positions of the bird dog you will undoubtedly get stronger faster by virtue of improved biomechanics.

Our @kabuki_virtualcoaching team films and produces FREE high quality educational content like this every day for the community. If you follow our brand, you are missing out big time if you don’t also follow @kabuki_virtualcoaching. Check out some of the latest videos they’ve posted and drop suggestions or video requests in the comments below.
-
Building an effective arch for bench pressing is not just for powerlifters. Global tension is important for maximizing energy transfer and establishing a good base for your shoulder girdle to work from. Global tension does not mean reducing the range of motion thought that could be a goal of most bench pressers.

Global tension allows the entire spine to be equally loaded which reduces the acute loading at the lumbar spine.

Video Highlights:

- Focus on uprighting and extending your upper back first and letting your lower back arch to the amount necessary

- Unless you only want to improve your bench press dont focus on reducing your range if motion. Exercises that have a high mechanic tension tension and large ROM are the bread and butter of hypertrophy training. Reducing the ROM only means less muscle mass gain in most situations.

A few weeks back we released a free resource for those who wish to DIY their own rack! Link in story, and make sure to check our free DIY Barbell plan as well!
•••
#repost @mad_scientist_duffin
-
This may be controversial to say as an equipment supplier, but yes, a well-made DIY Wood Rack can be both viable and safe. At @kabukistrength we would rather see people lifting than not.
-
Many folks as of late have been unable to access equipment or are on limited budgets, but that shouldn’t keep you from training. I grew up homeless and living in wilderness shacks (see last post), and I still found a way to train and get the work in. I love seeing the ingenuity of simply getting it done so you can train, and was inspired to see what I could put together for a small budget.
-
As an engineer and equipment manufacturer, I want to take a stance and say that this is viable option, provide you some inspiration for ideas, and even some prints our design engineer put together for your DIY project. In all honesty, these are better alternatives than a cheap-o rack from Amazon or Walmart.  This is also a great way to keep training while saving up for a better rack. I built this one for less than $75 and in under 1 hour!
-
Swipe up on my story or head over to www.kabukistrength.com/DIY and we’ll email you a PDF containing technical drawings and a materials list you can get started with. Have fun and build safe!
-
PS. Watch ‘till the end to see me take my creation for a ride with some heavy squats!
-

With a rapidly changing fitness landscape, barbells are seemingly harder and harder to come by. Our engineering manager Adam has come up with a simple, affordable DIY solution for making your own barbell using materials you can buy locally and/or online. We believe strength training and fitness should be accessible to anyone, and this is our initiative to provide free, high quality DIY plans and ideas to the community. #KabukiDIY #DIYBarbell
-
Depending on how savvy of a shopper you are, you can build this bar for between $50-$75, maybe even less. Watch this video to learn more + swipe up on our story or visit kabukistrength.com/DIY to download the PDF with technical drawings, material list, sourcing info, and more instruction.
-
Have any requests or ideas for what you would like to see DIY plans for next? Drop them in the comments below!

node.text:
Today's guest is the legendary @tmacsinc, a retired SpecOps operator who is now one of the top instructors in tactical training, marksmanship, and performance-based physical training for the tactically-minded through his company @combatstrengthtraining. 
Our hosts and Pat discuss general preparedness, fitness, proficiency, and the differences in preparing for dynamic, multi-plane human function as is necessary in a tactical environment. Pat draws from his experiences as a member of 1st SFOD-D (Delta Force) in hostile areas to work with individuals in a variety of skillsets outside of just marksmanship. He talks us through his combat strength training program and the kind of training methodologies and philosophies they draw from.

Thanks for joining us on Strength Chat @tmacsinc
PODCAST SIGNATURE •
Hope you enjoy! As always, please leave us a review and tell all your friends about Strength Chat 🙂
•••••
Hosted by the Mad Scientist of Strength, Dr. Rudolph, and The Wizard of Training. @mad_scientist_duffin @rudykadlub @brandon_senn
•••••
Available on iTunes, Spotify, YouTube, IGTV, Google Play, and Stitcher as well! Make sure to subscribe!

How do you approach technique work? Is it based on a perception of what a squat “should look like” or is it grounded in sound biomechanical principles about how the body functions?
-
We find that people start at the wrong place when they want to improve their technique. Following a process is the best way to improve almost every component of training and improving your technique is no different.
-
Positions > Drills > Soft Tissue Work
-
DID YOU KNOW that Kabuki Strength has a full-time staff of coaches working at the Lab who produce educational content like the video above, teach continuing ed. courses all over the world, and work with hundreds of strength athletes to help them reach their goals?
-
In fact, we consider ourselves an education company first - a characteristic that bleeds into every aspect of our organization - from the equipment we manufacture, the content we produce, and the incredible folks we work with. Here is a fantastic example of the kind of content you will find for free, posted daily, on our @kabuki_virtualcoaching page.
-
If you’d like to learn more about our education and coaching services or talk to a coach via a free strategy call, hit the link in our story!

Excalibur? More like ExcaliBar. If you’ve ever had to deal with a bar jammed in a bar stand, you know the sword-stuck-in-stone struggle🏰.⁣
⁣
But the Duffalo Bar justifies such a struggle. One look at the Duffalo's propriety multi-radius bend and you know it’s a bar worthy of the most harrowing of quests for strength. The Duffalo's unique design makes it a shoulder-friendly option for both bench and squat work. The Duffalo Bar has helped athletes around the world stay healthier in training so they can be ready to carry out crown-earning feats in their sport 👑.⁣
⁣
Swipe up in today’s story to learn more about what the Duffalo can do for you and your training. You can get one from Kabuki Strength without having to be the one true King—we promise.⁣

Four Kadillac Bars, one @ghoststrongequipment combo rack, and one @kabuki_virtualcoaching coach with a death wish--can coach @kyle_kabuki hit four movements for three reps each with the Kadillac Bar loaded to 135 in under one minute (no tampering with the frame rate on this one-take clip, scout’s honor)? We decided to do some performance testing in the Kabuki Strength Lab and find out. We're not saying try this at home, but the 1-Minute Kadillac Gauntlet was definitely a challenge.⁣
⁣
The Kadillac Bar is incredibly versatile--and it's useful for more than just the four movements shown in this video. Rows, pull-ups, press variations, curls, and more--the Kadillac bar gives you multiple training options and it does so in a neutral grip, joint-friendly way. Get in on the Kadillac versatility train--gauntlet optional--swipe up in today's story to learn more about this amazing bar.⁣
